<article>
    <h1>Ro&#xAD;bots res&#xAD;cue coun&#xAD;try&#x2019;s poor from in&#xAD;hu&#xAD;man, caste-driven prac&#xAD;tice</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201217/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-17"><time>2020-12-17</time></a>
        - <span>WORLD</span>
        - <span role="byline">De&#xAD;barshi Das&#xAD;gupta</span>
    </section>

    <p>Thanks to ini­tia­tives en­abled by tech­nol­ogy, some In­dian work­ers could be spared the in­hu­man prac­tice of hav­ing to go into sew­ers to man­u­ally clean them.</p>
    <p>Ker­ala-based Gen­robotics In­no­va­tions has de­vel­oped Bandi­coot, a ma­chine with a cam­er­amounted ex­tend­able robotic arm that de­scends into man­holes and scoops out dirt.</p>
    <p>It is con­nected to a sep­a­rate unit that in­cludes a vis­ual dis­play and con­trols for the op­er­a­tor.</p>
    <p>Gen­robotics has sold more than 50 of its ro­bots since they</p>
    <p>were launched in Oc­to­ber 2018.</p>
    <p>The Bandi­coot is cur­rently in use in more than 25 cities across 11 states.</p>
    <p>Gen­robotics en­tered i nto a man­u­fac­tur­ing part­ner­ship with Tata Group ear­lier this year.</p>
    <p>It plans to start its own pro­duc­tion fa­cil­ity in Coimbatore, Tamil Nadu, next year.</p>
    <p>Sewer Croc is an­other tech­based so­lu­tion that has gained pop­u­lar­ity.</p>
    <p>Also fit­ted with a cam­era, it in­cor­po­rates a robotic sys­tem that dis­in­te­grates and flushes out block­ages in sew­ers.</p>
    <p>Un­for­tu­nately, the high cost of the ma­chines re­mains a de­ter­rent to their wider use – a Bandi­coot ma­chine, for in­stance, costs around 2.5 mil­lion ru­pees (S$45,000).</p>
    <p>But Mr Rashid K, the co</p>
    <p>founder and di­rec­tor of Gen­robotics, told The Straits Times he is op­ti­mistic that re­newed gov­ern­ment sup­port for mech­a­nised clean­ing will make these ma­chines more ac­ces­si­ble.</p>
    <p>Gen­robotics has trained more than 700 work­ers to use its ma­chines.</p>
    <p>The en­cour­ag­ing feed­back from these in­di­vid­u­als, who have bro­ken free from the cast­edriven in­jus­tice of scav­eng­ing, keeps Mr Rashid K. and his col­leagues go­ing.</p>
    <p>At a re­cent gath­er­ing, one such group of work­ers told him that “their en­tire gen­er­a­tion will re­mem­ber the Bandi­coot team for­ever”.</p>
    <p>“We don’t re­quire any­thing more than that,” Mr Rashid K. said.</p>

